UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1513
1 at least two former employees of the Kentucky Transportation Cabinet, are facing federal
2 charges for mail fraud and unlawful production of identification documents, as well as
3 money laundering conspiracy, arising from a scheme by Kentucky Transportation
4 Cabinet employees that resulted in the issuance of invalid licenses to noncitizens of the
5 United States who are alleged to have paid up to $200 for each illegally obtained license
6 and without being required to demonstrate their qualifications to drive on the roads of this
7 Commonwealth, resulting in more than 1,500 driver's licenses being revoked; and
8 WHEREAS, a court ruled that the Kentucky Transportation Cabinet violated the
9 Commonwealth's open records laws by withholding documents tied to the investigation
10 into immigrants illegally obtaining Kentucky driver's licenses; and
11 WHEREAS, the Auditor of Public Accounts recently released findings following a
12 review of executive branch spending in fiscal year 2025 based upon eMars data that
13 revealed extravagant spending of tax dollars, including over $183,500 spent by the
14 Department of Kentucky State Police on out-of-state travel costs while providing security
15 to Governor Andy Beshear and other members of his staff, with a limousine charge in
16 Germany in excess of $7,500; and
17 WHEREAS, the findings of the Auditor also included advertising expenditures of
18 executive branch entities in excess of $39,000,000 and out-of-state travel in excess of
19 $7,000,000; and
20 WHEREAS, the Auditor further found expenditures by the Kentucky Tourism, Arts
21 and Heritage Cabinet and the Governor's office in excess of $338,000 to a nonprofit
22 company for Kentucky Derby events, including a $17,000 dinner at a distillery; and
23 WHEREAS, other expenditures of the Beshear administration included over
24 $100,000 for Governor Andy Beshear to belong to the National Governors Association,
25 over $10,000,000 spent on "dues," and over $1,500,000 spent on promotional
26 entertainment;
27 NOW, THEREFORE,
Page 2 of 3
XXXX 3/6/2026 9:38 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1513
1 Be it resolved by the House of Representatives of the General Assembly of the
2 Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 Section 1. The Legislative Research Commission is urged to direct the staff of
4 the Legislative Oversight and Investigations Committee to investigate and review the
5 expenditures of the executive branch including but not limited to:
6 (1) Payment of fraudulent claims by the Office of Unemployment Insurance or
7 failure to pursue recovery of previously identified fraudulent claims paid;
8 (2) Medicaid program waste;
9 (3) Targeted enforcement by the Kentucky Department of Alcoholic Beverage
10 Control;
11 (4) Issuance of unlawful identification cards or operator's licenses;
12 (5) Unauthorized or wasteful spending on out-of-state travel, advertising, or
13 special events; and
14 (6) Violations of the Open Records Act.
15 Section 2. (1) It is requested that a report of the completed investigation
16 include:
17 (a) Misconduct engaged in by any individual and any action that was identified to
18 hold that individual accountable;
19 (b) Evidence of any failure to comply with existing statutory requirements or
20 administrative regulations; and
21 (c) Identification of the need and recommendations for changes to address greater
22 oversight of the expenditures of the executive branch, including potential statutory
23 changes.
24 (2) The report of any authorized investigation shall be submitted to the
25 Legislative Research Commission for referral to the Interim Joint Committees on
26 Appropriations and Revenue, State and Local Government, and Judiciary no later than
27 December 1, 2026.
